INTRODUCTION

The energy demand in Luzon keeps on growing each year. Many societal factors play a part in the energy generation and consumption of people in the largest island in the country and as such, experts as forecasting huge megawatt peaks in the year 2020. NGCP (National Grid Corporation) themselves said that Luzon will peak at around 12,286 megawatts during the dry season of the year. This growth though is still in line with the performance seen in the past months. Thus, forecasting the accurate demand per day is imperative, especially now that the country is slowly being overrun by the pandemic. More and more people have been staying inside their homes, in turn increasing each household's energy consumption in Luzon.

As mentioned earlier, accuracy in energy demand forecasting must be done with utmost importance and care. Allocating too much energy demand for a given time will result in energy wastage and more pollution. On the other hand, allocating little demand will result in more blackouts within the island. Such results are unfavorable at best. Thus, there is a need to have a method or procedure in which forecasting energy demand over the next hour will be as close to the real generated energy demand as possible.

PROBLEM STATEMENT

In dealing with forecasting energy, accuracy should be of high regard. As per the source of this data, a plus-minus of 3% is the industry standard for forecasts. The problem however is that there is no way to accurately predict what the energy demand will be. Even if seasonality and past trends were used in computations, it's always a gamble to say that this certain figure will be the exact demand. An incorrect prediction, no matter how small, is costly but that's the price one has to pay.

The aim of this analysis, however, is to not submit to those thresholds, but rather to make an accurate forecast as close to the real value as possible. Thus, in this analysis, I sought to answer the following question: How can we create an almost-accurate energy demand forecasting model for Luzon?

The answer may lie in the use of Machine Learning.

EXPERIMENTS

Data¶

The data was given to me by an employee of a private energy trading agency. It has around 1 year worth energy demand listed at hourly intervals. For this analysis however, data from May to July was used. I assumed that using three months of hourly data is enough to capture a trend on energy demand.

Terminologies¶

Some of the following terms will be seen in the dataset and for clarity, these are defined here:

  • DAP: Day Ahead Prediction. Initial predictions done by the company.
  • RTX: Real Time Ex-post. Real time demand recorded.
  • RTD: Real Time Dispatch. Initial demand recorded within the first few minutes of the hour
  • Features/Columns: Variables that are essential for determining the outcome of the machine learning model.
  • Classification/Regression: Types of the machine learning model. Classification models have an outcome of categorical data and regression models have an outcome of continuous, often numerical variables.

The following was the pipeline followed regarding this analysis:

THE DATASET

This data was provided by a friend who works in a private energy trading company that allocates non-renewable and renewable energy for the whole island of Luzon and he provided me with 3 months worth of hourly data. Their current problem was that they wanted to find out if one can predict hourly energy demand based on expected temperature and weather data. The data had these features:

feature meaning data type
Date recorded date of demand datetime
Month month derived from date str
Day day of the week str
Interval refers to the hours within the day float
DAP DEMAND day-ahead prediction. the initial day ahead forecasts of the company float
RTD DEMAND real time demand. initial deman recorded at the start of interval float
RTX DEMAND real-time expost. total demand recorded for an interval float
Temp day temperature int
Weather forecasted weather condition str
Wind forecasted wind conditions int
Humidity forecasted humidity measure int

DATA WRANGLING

To make the data easier to analyze, some features were derived to better understand how the data would look like. The intervals were labeled based on what time of the day it was and the Day was labeled weekend or weekday. Some columns were renamed as well for easier coding.

In [3]:
def interval_label(row):
    if row['Interval'] >= 1 and row['Interval'] < 6 or row['Interval'] == 24:
        return 'Dawn'
    elif row['Interval'] >= 6 and row['Interval'] < 12:
        return 'Morning'
    elif row['Interval'] >= 12 and row['Interval'] <= 17:
        return 'Afternoon'
    else:
        return 'Evening'
    
def label_day(row):
    if row['Day'] == 'Sat':
        return 'Weekend'
    elif row['Day'] == 'Sun':
        return 'Weekend'
    else:
        return 'Weekday'
    
df_copy['Date'] = df_copy['Date'].str.split('/', expand=True).drop([0, 2], axis=1)
df_copy['day_category'] = df_copy.apply(lambda row: label_day(row), axis=1 )
df_copy['interval_label'] = df_copy.apply(lambda row: interval_label(row), axis=1)
df_copy = df_copy.rename(columns={'DAP DEMAND':'DAP', 'RTD DEMAND':'RTD', 
                                  'RTX DEMAND': 'RTX'})
df_copy = df_copy.dropna()

Prior to proceeding with the analysis, some features will be one hot encoded. Since these are categorical labels, one-hot encoding them will make it easier for the model to analyze them.

Figure 3: Average hourly RTX Demands for the past 3 months.

Here are some insights we could come up with:

  • The most minimal RTX average we could see is around 7000kwh. From here, we can see how much electricity Luzon is consuming. 7000kwh is large enough already. We could see that at dawn to around early morning, people consume this much energy already. Since it is quarantine, some might be having all nighters because of classes, or simply netflixing til the sun rises.
  • RTX spikes at around midday to early afternoon. These are probably the hottest hours the day so maybe the people are turning on their airconditioning units. This is also the time wherein most people are swamped with work regarding their jobs or classes. Most devices like laptops, internet, and other gadgets are switched on during this time.

ESTABLISHING A BASELINE

Prior to creating a model, error statistics for the the initial DAP Demand was calculated.

In [8]:
#Calculating MAE, MSE and MAPE
def mean_absolute_percentage_error(y_true, y_pred): 
    y_true, y_pred = np.array(y_true), np.array(y_pred)
    return np.mean(np.abs((y_true - y_pred) / y_true)) * 100

MAPE = mean_absolute_percentage_error(df_copy.RTX, df_copy.DAP)
MAE = mean_absolute_error(df_copy.RTX, df_copy.DAP)
RMSE = sqrt(mean_squared_error(df_copy.RTX, df_copy.DAP))
R2 = r2_score(df_copy.RTX, df_copy.DAP)

columns = ['model', 'MAE', 'RMSE', 'MAPE', 'R2']
errors = pd.DataFrame(columns=columns)
errors.loc[0] = ['initial', MAE, RMSE, MAPE, R2]

def plot_feature_importances_energy(model):
    n_features=X1.shape[1]

    plt.yticks(np.arange(n_features), X1.columns)

If the hour is expected to be colder, of course lesser energy must be allocated, and the opposite is when the hour is expected to have peak high temperatures.

KEY LEARNINGS

In summary, these were the things that I learned while making this study:

  • Domain knowledge is an advantage for these types of problems. I for one know little about forecasting energy demands so it helped that I asked knowledgable people on it and reading as well lots of journals and research papers on the topic.
  • It gave a good result just for 3 months worth of hourly data BUT I believe the seasonality and the extraordinary pandemic situation wasn't captured by my model. For this to be happen, I should've used 1 or 2 years worth of data. This model will be robust for the next few months but I doubt if it is usable in the next year or so.
  • Multicollinearity is the enemy of these types of datasets. During my first run of the analysis, I one hot encoded the months and the days BUT i kept the date column. I also kept the DAP and RTD columns. It gave me a false sense of security (the model was able to achieve 98% accuracy). I should've run PCC or LSA on it but given the small number of features, I just removed those that I think are similar (kept dates, removed months and days).
